node.title: Idaho Will Ban Most Abortions, Charge Those Who Perform Them if Roe V. Wade Overturned
node.description: The law would ban abortions except in cases of rape, incest or danger to a mother's life and could go into effect within a month if Roe v. Wade is overturned.

node.title: Sports Host Fired for 2016 Audio of Racist Remarks Against Native Americans
node.description: He said the audio was "obtained illegally" and was released as "one man's malicious actions against myself and my family."

node.title: Amazon Workers Will Vote Again on Whether to Join Union Despite Company's Opposition
node.description: The decision by NLRB Regional Director Lisa Henderson released Monday accused the retail giant of having "hijacked" the first vote by misleading employees.

node.title: Potential Jurors in Kim Potter Trial Asked Similar Questions to Those From Chauvin Case
node.description: The potential jurors will have their opinions on policing, protests, and Black Lives Matter and Blue Lives Matter movements reviewed by attorneys.

node.title: Cars to give way to turtles on one of Australia's most famous beaches
node.description: Cars are set to be banned from Broome's Cable Beach during turtle nesting season in a move that could protect 80 per cent of the tiny hatchlings as they try to reach the sea.

node.title: NRL investigates Brandon Smith's podcast appearance
node.description: Melbourne hooker Brandon Smith is being investigated for his use of foul language on a recent podcast, while the Storm are reportedly furious about him discussing his potential move to the Roosters.

node.title: Could leasing nuclear submarines from the US address Australia's capability gap?
node.description: A former US navy intelligence officer says leasing US Los Angeles Class nuclear submarines should be considered to promptly upskill the Australian navy workforce and deal with an increasing threat from China.

node.title: Ghislaine Maxwell is on trial on sex abuse charges. Here's what it was like inside the courtroom
node.description: The first day in Ghislaine Maxwell's sex abuse trial sets the stage for an argument over whether she was a predator and "partner in crime" or a scapegoat taken advantage of by deceased financier Jeffrey Epstein.

node.title: Vaccine mandate to be expanded 'to protect vulnerable Queenslanders'
node.description: Queensland will mandate COVID-19 vaccines for all staff at state and private schools, childcare centres, correctional facilities and airports, Premier Annastacia Palaszczuk says.

node.title: New Omicron case found in NSW, has been active in community
node.description: The number of cases of the Omicron COVID-19 variant grows to five after a new infection is discovered. The ABC understands a woman in her 30s visited several venues on the Central Coast while infectious.

node.title: Scientist who helped discover Omicron variant warns of its potential
node.description: The Omicron variant has more than 50 mutations, enhancing the virus' ability to infect the body.

node.title: Ghislaine Maxwell’s Trial Opens, With Epstein at Its Center
node.description: A prosecutor described Jeffrey Epstein and his longtime girlfriend and associate, Ms. Maxwell, as “partners in crime.”

node.title: Boebert Reaches Out to Omar After Incendiary Video, Escalating a Feud
node.description: Representative Lauren Boebert made an overture to Representative Ilhan Omar after suggesting that the Muslim lawmaker was a terrorism threat. The call did not go well.

node.title: The defense department says Oklahoma National Guard must get vaccinated.
node.description: The governor had tried to exempt the troops from the federal vaccine requirement that applies to all service branches.

node.title: Consumers Spending Less This Holiday Season, But Retailers Are Still Raking in Billions
node.description: Black Friday deals aren't the same this year. Shoppers are expected to pay 5 percent to 17 percent more for items like clothes, TV and appliances.

node.title: Ghislaine Maxwell Merely 'Scapegoat' for 'Man Who Behaved Badly,' Defense Says in Opening
node.description: "She's not Jeffrey Epstein. She's not like Jeffrey Epstein" or any of the powerful men, moguls and media giants who abuse women, attorney Bobbi Sternheim said.

node.title: Lee Elder, the first Black golfer to play in the Masters, dies at 87
node.description: Elder, who fought through numerous obstacles to become the first Black golfer to play in the Masters, died at the age of 87, the PGA Tour announced Monday.

node.title: Here's What We Know About Chris Cuomo's Efforts to Help His Brother Amid Ethics Concerns
node.description: The former governor's allies assisted him with strategizing his case and how to save his political career, according to released testimony.

node.title: New Drug That Helps Identify Ovarian Cancer Is Approved by FDA
node.description: Cytalux could help surgeons identify ovarian tumors during surgery, potentially improving outcomes for those with the female reproductive system cancer.

node.title: Barbados to become a republic, replacing Queen with current Governor-General
node.description: Famed for stunning beaches and a love of cricket, Barbados will this week replace its head of state, Queen Elizabeth II, with her current representative, Governor-General Sandra Mason.

node.title: Westpac admits to charging 11,000 dead customers, ASIC sues for 'widespread' breaches
node.description: The corporate regulator has launched six court cases against Westpac for alleged, widespread compliance failures that affected 11,000 dead consumers and the bank could face a $113 million fine.

node.title: Impending heatwave could turn 'Australia's hottest town' into the hottest place on Earth
node.description: With the mercury tipped to soar past 40C and stay there for parts of northern WA, authorities are urging residents to look after themselves and stay fire safe.

node.title: Susan Neill-Fraser loses appeal against murder conviction
node.description: Hobart woman Susan Neill-Fraser's appeal against her murder conviction has been dismissed by the Court of Criminal Appeal.

node.title: Greg Hunt says Omicron appears to be 'manageable', border pause only temporary
node.description: Federal Health Minister Greg Hunt says the government's "overwhelming view" is that the Omicron variant is "manageable" and that advice is that it may be milder than other variants.

node.title: David Gulpilil, Famed Aboriginal Actor, Dies at 68
node.description: In a career that began with the film “Walkabout” 50 years ago, he was acclaimed for changing the way Australia’s Indigenous people were portrayed and viewed.

node.title: Iron Bowl Thriller Behind It, Alabama Prepares for No. 1 Georgia
node.description: Alabama is poised to move up a spot in the College Football Playoff rankings ahead of its Southeastern Conference title game against the Bulldogs.

node.title: A Song for Stephen Sondheim, by Julie Andrews and Others
node.description: Readers recount their interactions with the composer. Ms. Andrews laments the loss of a “genius.”

node.title: With Omicron’s Arrival, Stocks Will Again Hang on Headlines
node.description: Stocks rose on Monday, but analysts expect a bumpy ride for share prices while experts assess whether existing vaccines will be effective against the new variant.

node.title: Elizabeth Holmes Says Former Boyfriend Abused Her
node.description: Ms. Holmes, the founder of the failed blood testing start-up Theranos, blamed Ramesh Balwani, the former No. 2 at the company.

node.title: 4 takeaways from the first day of Ghislaine Maxwell’s trial.
node.description: In the coming weeks, jurors are expected to hear testimony from four women whom prosecutors say Jeffrey Epstein exploited for sex with Ms. Maxwell’s help.
